Create a Leaflet Map from Google Sheets Data

In this Notebook, well make a leaflet map using data from Google Sheets.

Import San Francisco Public Library Locations from Google Sheets

Start by importing the sf_libraries sheet from the following Google Spreadsheet (which can be viewed by anyone with the link):

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Zm3BkQaW4vuk-X4L_6BOhFEyCr3HO_kSMktd-rHyXG8/.


To import, were going to need the Google Sheet ID (which you can read from the URL):

gsheet_id <- "1Zm3BkQaW4vuk-X4L_6BOhFEyCr3HO_kSMktd-rHyXG8"


Load the googlesheets4 package:

library(googlesheets4)


Our Google Sheet is open to anyone with the link, so we dont need to be signed-in. To avoid a password prompt, lets sign-out with gs4_deauth():

gs4_deauth()

Import the sf_libraries sheet using range_read():

## Download Sheet1
sf_libraries_tbl <- range_read(ss = gsheet_id, 
                               sheet = "sf_libraries", 
                               range = NULL)
Reading from "Libraries and Breweries"
Range "'sf_libraries'"


View what we got:

We can see theres a lon and lat column in there, so we dont have to geocode the addresses.

Lets create a version of this tibble containing only the columns we actually need in our interactive map:

library(dplyr, quietly = TRUE)

sf_lib4map_tbl <- sf_libraries_tbl %>% 
  dplyr::select(branch, address, city, state, zip, phone, lon, lat)
sf_lib4map_tbl


Create a sf data frame

The next step is turn the data frame into a sf data frame.

The coordinates are already in geographic coordinates (i.e., longitude & latitude), so we dont need to (un)project the points. However we do need to tell sf what the CRS is (4236 is the EPSG number for geographic coordinates with WGS 84 datum).

library(sf, quietly = TRUE)
sf_lib4map_sf <- st_as_sf(sf_lib4map_tbl, coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326)
sf_lib4map_sf
Simple feature collection with 28 features and 6 fields
geometry type:  POINT
dimension:      XY
bbox:           xmin: -122.4983 ymin: 37.71262 xmax: -122.3914 ymax: 37.80253
geographic CRS: WGS 84


Create an Interactive Map with tmap

Load tmap and set the mode to view (interactive):

library(tmap, quietly = TRUE)
tmap_mode("view")
tmap mode set to interactive viewing


The most basic tmap involves a tm_shape() (to define the data for a layer) plus a function to draw features (like tm_symbols()):

tm_shape(sf_lib4map_sf) +
  tm_symbols()

Lets change the basemap to OpenStreetMap. (Note: you can view all of the available basemaps by typing providers$ in the code chunk or console.)

tm_shape(sf_lib4map_sf) +
  tm_symbols(col = "blue", size = 0.8) +
tm_basemap(providers$OpenStreetMap)


Lastly well modify the pop-up windows with the popup.vars argument:

tm_shape(sf_lib4map_sf) +
  tm_symbols(col = "blue", size = 0.8, popup.vars = c("address", "city", "state", "zip", "phone")) +
tm_basemap(providers$OpenStreetMap)


Create an Interactive Map with leaflet

The leaflet package can also be used to make interactive maps. leaflet provides a few more customization options, including the ability to customize the pop-up windows with our own HTML text.

First we create a character vector of HTML code we want to appear in the popup windows:

## Create a character vector of HTML code for the pop-up windows
my_popup_html <- sf_lib4map_sf %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  transmute(popup_html = paste0("<b>", branch, "</b><br/>", 
                                address, "<br/>", 
                                city, ", ", state, " ", zip, "<br/>", 
                                "tel: ", phone)) %>% 
  pull(popup_html)

head(my_popup_html)
[1] "<b>ANZA</b><br/>550 37th Ave.<br/>San Francisco, CA 94121<br/>tel: (415) 355-5717"                                      
[2] "<b>BAYVIEW / LINDA BROOKS-BURTON</b><br/>5075 Third St.<br/>San Francisco, CA 94124<br/>tel: (415) 355-5757"            
[3] "<b>BERNAL HEIGHTS</b><br/>500 Cortland Ave.<br/>San Francisco, CA 94110<br/>tel: (415) 355-2810"                        
[4] "<b>CHINATOWN / HIM MARK LAI</b><br/>1135 Powell St.<br/>San Francisco, CA 94108<br/>tel: (415) 355-2888"                
[5] "<b>EUREKA VALLEY / HARVEY MILK MEMORIAL</b><br/>1 Jose Sarria Court<br/>San Francisco, CA 94114<br/>tel: (415) 355-5616"
[6] "<b>EXCELSIOR</b><br/>4400 Mission St.<br/>San Francisco, CA 94112<br/>tel: (415) 355-2868"


Now were ready to create the map in leaflet:

library(leaflet)

## Create the leaflet map
library_leaf <- leaflet(sf_lib4map_sf) %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(popup = my_popup_html, radius = 5, stroke = FALSE, fillOpacity = 0.7)

## Display the leaflet map
library_leaf

Click on one of the circles to view the custom HTML code we created for the popup windows
